pullRequest.body:
This change proves that `Grothendieck.pre F G` is an equivalence if `G` is an equivalence. An essential ingredient in the proof is the `transport` construction: Given a morphism in the base category, `transport` yields a map between fibers of the Grothendieck construction.

This PR is part of the effort to prove the Freyd-Mitchell embedding theorem.

---

We should not use `Equivalance.mk` as it leaves out a compatibility which we should be able to obtain here.

```suggestion
@[simps]
def transport (x : Grothendieck F) {c : C} (t : x.base  c) : Grothendieck F :=
```
I'm unsure whether this would be an improvement. `transport` is not a super-simple definition. If simp unfolds it automatically, expressions might get more complicated quickly.

```suggestion
@[simps]
def toTransport (x : Grothendieck F) {c : C} (t : x.base  c) : x  x.transport t :=
  t,  _
```

```suggestion
  hom := .inv, eqToHom (by
    dsimp
    rw [ Functor.comp_obj,  Cat.comp_eq_comp,  F.map_comp, .hom_inv_id, F.map_id,
      Cat.id_obj])
  inv := x.toTransport .hom
  hom_inv_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by simp)
  inv_hom_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by simp)
```

```suggestion
    pre F G  map (whiskerRight .hom F)  (pre F H) :=
```

```suggestion
def preInv (G : D  C) : Grothendieck F  Grothendieck (G.functor  F) :=
  map (F.leftUnitor.inv  whiskerRight G.counitInv F  (Functor.associator _ _ _).hom) 
    Grothendieck.pre (G.functor  F) G.inverse
```
I removed `leftUnitor` and `associator` -- they are just `rfl` and somehow seem to break `preEquivalence`.

```suggestion
def mapWhiskerLeftIsoConjPreMap {F' : C  Cat} (G : D  C) ( : F  F') :
    map (whiskerLeft G.functor ) 
      (preEquivalence F G).functor  map   (preEquivalence F' G).inverse := by
  apply Iso.symm
  apply preEquivalence F' G |>.congrRight.fullyFaithfulFunctor.preimageIso
  exact isoWhiskerLeft ((preEquivalence F G).functor  map ) (preEquivalence F' G).counitIso
```
(The docstring should also be updated.)

```suggestion
def preEquivalence (G : D  C) : Grothendieck (G.functor  F)  Grothendieck F where
  functor := pre F G.functor
  inverse := preInv F G
```
Also, the unit and counit isos should not be constructed using tactics. This would create issues when we want to unfold these definitions.
